1` takes `t01` (which is now the SUM output) and `c00` → WRONG inputs\n\nSo the propagate gate `AND(partialSum, carry)` should use `z01` (the partial sum wire) and `c00`. Let me look... `findGate('AND', z01, c00)` - is there a gate with inputs `z01` and `c00`? No! The gate has inputs `t01` and `c00`. So `propGate` is null, `propagate = ''`.\n\nThis means the carry computation at bit 1 breaks. `carryGate` would look for `OR(a01, '')` which won't work.\n\nThe fundamental issue is: when partialSum wire is swapped (e.g., `t01`→`z01`), the consumer gates that used the old name (`t01`) as input now get the wrong value. In the original circuit, gates reference `t01` as input. After the swap, `t01` is output by a different gate (the sum gate), so those consumer gates now get a different value.\n\nBut my algorithm needs to find `AND(partialSum, carry)` where `partialSum = z01`. There's no such AND gate because the AND gate still uses the input name `t01`.\n\nSo the algorithm can't find the propagate gate because the propagate gate uses the OLD name of the partial sum wire. This is inherent to the swap — the partial sum is now named `z01`, but the AND gate's input still says `t01`.\n\nWait, I need to re-examine this. The swap only changes OUTPUT wire names. The INPUT wire names of all gates remain unchanged. So after swapping `t01` and `z01`:\n- Gate that XORs x01,y01: output changed from `t01` to `z01`\n- Gate that XORs partial_sum,carry: output changed from `z01` to `t01`\n\nBut the second gate's INPUTS are still `t01` and `c00`. The wire `t01` used to come from the first gate, but now `t01` comes from the second gate (itself). That would be a cycle! That can't be right.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The swap exchanges the `out` field of two gates. So:\n- Gate A: `x01 XOR y01 -> t01` becomes `x01 XOR y01 -> z01` \n- Gate B: `t01 XOR c00 -> z01` becomes `t01 XOR c00 -> t01`\n\nGate B reads `t01` as input and writes `t01` as output. That's self-referencing but in the simulation it would be fine since `t01` is now produced by a different gate... wait no, `t01` is produced by Gate B itself now. But Gate B needs `t01` as input. In the simulation, `t01` wouldn't have a value until Gate B fires, but Gate B can't fire until `t01` has a value. This is a deadlock!\n\nSo this swap configuration actually creates a circuit that can't be simulated (or would deadlock). That means my test case is invalid. Let me reconsider what valid swaps look like.\n\nA valid swap must exchange two gate output wires such that the circuit remains acyclic (though it'll compute wrong results). Swapping `t01` with `z01` creates a self-loop on `t01`, which is invalid.\n\nLet me create more realistic test cases where swaps don't create cycles. In the actual problem, the swaps involve gates whose outputs aren't directly used as inputs by each other in a way that creates cycles.\n\nLet me think about which swaps are safe in the 4-bit adder:\n- Swapping `z01` with `a01`: Gate `t01 XOR c00 -> a01`, Gate `x01 AND y01 -> z01`. `z01` feeds no gate at bit 1 (it's an output), and `a01` feeds the OR gate. Safe.\n- Swapping `z01` with `c01`: Gate `t01 XOR c00 -> c01`, Gate `a01 OR b01 -> z01`. `z01` isn't used as input by bit-1 gates (it's a z-output), and `c01` feeds bit-2 gates. Safe.\n- Swapping `z01` with `b01`: Gate `t01 XOR c00 -> b01`, Gate `t01 AND c00 -> z01`. Safe since `b01` feeds the OR gate and `z01` isn't used locally.\n- Swapping `t01` with `z01`: Creates the self-loop issue described above. INVALID.\n\nSo my \"partial-sum swapped with z wire\" test case is invalid because it creates cycles. Let me fix the tests."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2717,"cache_read_input_tokens":60782,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2717},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_i